```matlab
% Define variables
g = 9.81;       % gravitational acceleration
L = 1;          % length of pendulum
tmax = 10;      % maximum time
theta0 = 0.1;   % initial angular displacement of pendulum
omega0 = 0;     % initial angular velocity of pendulum
tstep = 0.01;   % time step

% Define Hamiltonian
syms theta(t) omega(t)
H = 1/2 * L^2 * omega^2 - g * L * cos(theta);

% Define equations of motion
eqns = [
    diff(theta,t) == diff(H,omega),
    diff(omega,t) == -diff(H,theta)
];

% Define initial conditions
conds = [theta(0) == theta0, omega(0) == omega0];

% Solve equations of motion
vars = [theta, omega];
sol = dsolve(eqns, conds);

% Plot solution
t = 0:tstep:tmax;
thetasol = double(subs(sol.theta, 't', t));
plot(t, thetasol)
xlabel('Time (s)');
ylabel('Angular displacement (rad)');
title('Simple Pendulum');
```

In this script, we first define the variables `g`, `L`, `tmax`, `theta0`, `omega0`, and `tstep` for the gravitational acceleration, length of the pendulum, maximum time, initial angular displacement of the pendulum, initial angular velocity of the pendulum, and time step, respectively.

Next, we define the Hamiltonian of the simple pendulum as `H`, using the MATLAB symbolic toolbox. The variables `theta` and `omega` are also defined as symbolic functions of time.

Then, we define the equations of motion derived from the Hamiltonian. These equations are stored in the variable `eqns`, with the first equation representing the derivative of position (theta) with respect to time and the second equation representing the derivative of velocity (omega) with respect to time.

Finally, we solve the equations of motion using `dsolve`, which uses the initial conditions specified in `conds` to compute the general solution. We then plot the solution using `plot`, with time as the x-axis and the angular displacement as the y-axis. The resulting plot shows the motion of the simple pendulum over time.
